   abstract = {Interfaces between polarity domains in nitride semiconductors, the so-called Inversion Domain Boundaries (IDB), have been widely described, both theoretically and experimentally, as perfect interfaces (without dislocations and vacancies). Although ideal planar IDBs are well documented, the understanding of their conﬁgurations and interactions inside crystals relies on perfect-interface assumptions. Here, we report on the microscopic conﬁguration of IDBs inside n-doped gallium nitride wires revealed by coherent X-ray Bragg imaging. Complex IDB conﬁgurations are evidenced with 6 nm resolution and the absolute polarity of each domain is unambiguously identiﬁed. Picoscale displacements along and across the wire are directly extracted from several Bragg reﬂections using phase retrieval algorithms, revealing rigid relative displacements of the domains and the absence of microscopic strain away from the IDBs. More generally, this method offers an accurate inner view of the displacements and strain of interacting defects inside small crystals that may alter optoelectronic properties of semiconductor devices.},
